div.span: You may be asked 3 different types of questions: multiple choice, true/false or yes/no. Answer each question by clicking the button to the left of the most appropriate response.
After you answer the last question, you will be given the chance to review and then submit your answers.
Please note that if you exit the quiz before clicking the Submit Answers button your answers will not be saved.

div.strong: Select the best response. The Dangerous Goods Safety Act 2004 (WA)…

Answer.Description: Is the first complete set of legislation that governs the use of hazardous goods in Western Australia.

Updates the legislation regulating the way that dangerous goods must be stored, handled and transported in Western Australia. It also introduces stricter licensing requirements for companies that handle dangerous goods.
Is a subset of the national regulations which include the Australian Code for the Transport of Dangerous Goods by Road and Rail, published in 2007.

span.strong: True or false? The Dangerous Goods Safety Act 2004 (WA) and its associated regulations replace the Explosives and Dangerous Goods Act 1961 (WA) and Dangerous Goods (Transport) Act 1998 (WA).
How many new supporting regulations are used in conjunction to the Dangerous Goods Safety Act 2004 (WA)?
Select the best response. Which of the following regulations are most relevant to your organisation?

Description.span: Dangerous Goods Safety (Storage and Handling of Non-explosives) Regulations 2007
Dangerous Goods Safety (Road and Rail Transport of Non-explosives) Regulations 2007

div.strong: Complete the statement with the correct response. Which of the following classes of dangerous goods are covered under the Western Australian dangerous goods safety legislation?

strong.span: The Act is designed to shift the responsibility for the management of dangerous goods from private industry to government.
places a general duty on companies to minimise risks associated with dangerous goods which may affect people, property and the environment.

True or false? The Act adopts a risk management approach to dangerous goods and requires industry participants to take all reasonably practical measures to manage these risks.
